But when I try using my model on ORT C++ code, it crashes in the line : 
```
auto inputOnnxTensor = Ort::Value::CreateTensor<float>(memoryInfo,
	inputValues.data(), inputValues.size(),
	inputShape.data(), inputShape.size());
```
A more thorough example below.

**Urgency**
We want to deploy our models in our company asap so it's urgent.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Windows 64 bits
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): nuget package from visual studio 2019
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.7.0
- Python version:
- Visual Studio version (if applicable): 2019
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source):
- CUDA/cuDNN version: no CUDA, we run our models on the CPU only
- GPU model and memory: no GPU, we run our models on the CPU only

**To Reproduce**
Here's the code used : 

```
#include <onnxruntime_cxx_api.h>
#include <assert.h>
#include <iostream>

int main() {

	Ort::Env env;

	// creates an inference session for a certain model
	Ort::Session session{ env, LR"(D:\GdPicture\dev\MachineLearning\OCR\models\ONNXModels\tflite_model_af.onnx)", Ort::SessionOptions{} };

	// Ort::Session gives access to input and output information:
	// - count
	// - name
	// - shape and type
	std::cout << "Number of model inputs: " << session.GetInputCount() << "\n";
	std::cout << "Number of model outputs: " << session.GetOutputCount() << "\n";

	// you can customize how allocation works. Let's just use a default allocator provided by the library
	Ort::AllocatorWithDefaultOptions allocator;
	// get input and output names
	auto* inputName = session.GetInputName(0, allocator);
	std::cout << "Input name: " << inputName << "\n";

	auto* outputName = session.GetOutputName(0, allocator);
	std::cout << "Output name: " << outputName << "\n";

	// get input shape
	auto inputShape = session.GetInputTypeInfo(0).GetTensorTypeAndShapeInfo().GetShape();

	size_t _input_tensor_size = 32 * 128 * 1;

	std::vector<float> inputValues(_input_tensor_size);

	// initialize input data with values in [0.0, 1.0]
	for (unsigned int i = 0; i < _input_tensor_size; i++)
		inputValues[i] = (float)i / (_input_tensor_size + 1);

	// where to allocate the tensors
	auto memoryInfo = Ort::MemoryInfo::CreateCpu(OrtDeviceAllocator, OrtMemTypeCPU);

	// create the input tensor (this is not a deep copy!)
	auto inputOnnxTensor = Ort::Value::CreateTensor<float>(memoryInfo,
		inputValues.data(), inputValues.size(),
		inputShape.data(), inputShape.size());

	return 0;
}
```
The model used is [tflite_model_af.zip](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/6148698/tflite_model_af.zip).

**Expected behavior**
I expected the program to run without any errors.


**Additional context**
The C++ code above works ok with other ONNX models that I found online. But with my custom model causes the program to crash (the model that I built using tensorflow 2 then made some optimizations and transformed it to tflite then finally used the tool tf2onnx to transform it to an onnx model).
Again, the model works fine when tested using onnxruntime in Python (using the python code above). But in C++ it crashes in the line mentioned above. Btw, I don't get any error message in the command line. I found out that the program was crashing in that specific line by looking at the call stack.

